<p>Also, here’s a question I had when solving <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/33238518/what-could-happen-if-i-dont-close-response-body">What happens if I don’t close <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">resp.Body?</code></a></p>

<p>READ THE BOOK DAWG.</p>

<hr />
<p><br />
Let’s start with Chapter 1.3</p>

<h2 id="finding-duplicate-lines">Finding Duplicate Lines</h2>

<p>This is a table to refer to for proper formatting (Standard C stuff tbh):</p>

<h2><img src="/_media/table02.jpg" alt="Table for Formatting" /></h2>
<p>I’m not going to share the code here. It’s a simple program that reads from <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">stdin</code> and prints out the lines that are repeated. I’m going to share the code for the next exercise, which is a bit more interesting.</p>

<h2 id="gifs">GIFs</h2>

<p>Go has a standard image package.
We got to make Lissajous figures. Code will be posted in the repo.</p>

<h2 id="fetching-urls-concurrently">Fetching URLs Concurrently</h2>

<p><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">ioutil.ReadAll</code> is now deprecated. Use <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">io.ReadAll</code> instead.</p>

<div class="language-go highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="k">package</span> <span class="n">main</span>

<span class="k">import</span> <span class="p">(</span>
	<span class="s">"fmt"</span>
	<span class="s">"io"</span>
	<span class="s">"net/http"</span>
	<span class="s">"os"</span>
<span class="p">)</span>

<span class="k">func</span> <span class="n">main</span><span class="p">()</span> <span class="p">{</span>
	<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">_</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">url</span> <span class="o">:=</span> <span class="k">range</span> <span class="n">os</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Args</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="m">1</span><span class="o">:</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="p">{</span>
		<span class="n">resp</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">err</span> <span class="o">:=</span> <span class="n">http</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Get</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">url</span><span class="p">)</span>
		<span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">err</span> <span class="o">!=</span> <span class="no">nil</span> <span class="p">{</span>
			<span class="n">fmt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Fprintf</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">os</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Stderr</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s">"fetch: %v</span><span class="se">\n</span><span class="s">"</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">err</span><span class="p">)</span>
			<span class="n">os</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Exit</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="m">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
		<span class="p">}</span>
		<span class="n">b</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">err</span> <span class="o">:=</span> <span class="n">io</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">ReadAll</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">resp</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Body</span><span class="p">)</span>
		<span class="n">resp</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Body</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Close</span><span class="p">()</span>
		<span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">err</span> <span class="o">!=</span> <span class="no">nil</span> <span class="p">{</span>
			<span class="n">fmt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Fprintf</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">os</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Stderr</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s">"fetch: reading %s: %v</span><span class="se">\n</span><span class="s">"</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">url</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">err</span><span class="p">)</span>
			<span class="n">os</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Exit</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="m">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
		<span class="p">}</span>
		<span class="n">fmt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Printf</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s">"%s"</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">b</span><span class="p">)</span>
	<span class="p">}</span>
<span class="p">}</span>

</code></pre></div></div>]]></content><author><name></name></author><category term="learning" /><category term="go" /><summary type="html"><![CDATA[One thing to add before we proceed, While doing the exercises in the book (1.3), I found out that ioutil.Discard has been deprecated, and now it is just io.Discard]]></summary></entry><entry><title type="html">Learning Go, Day 2</title><link href="http://localhost:4000/learning/go/2024/06/06/learning-go-day2.html" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="Learning Go, Day 2" /><published>2024-06-06T00:00:00-06:00</published><updated>2024-06-06T00:00:00-06:00</updated><id>http://localhost:4000/learning/go/2024/06/06/learning-go-day2</id><content type="html" xml:base="http://localhost:4000/learning/go/2024/06/06/learning-go-day2.html"><![CDATA[<p>Hello again,</p>

<p>Continuing from where we left off.</p>

<hr />
<p><br />
Let’s start with Chapter 1.2</p>

<h2 id="12-command-line-arguments">1.2 Command-Line Arguments</h2>

<p>The <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">os</code> package. The command line args are available to any program in a Variable named <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Args</code>. <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">os.Args</code> is a <em>slice</em> of strings. Can be accessed the same way as in Python.</p>

<p><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">os.Args[0]</code> is the name of the command.</p>

<p>I mean, if you look at the syntax. Shit is pretty similar to Python ngl.
<br />
Here.</p>

<div class="language-go highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="k">package</span> <span class="n">main</span>

<span class="k">import</span> <span class="p">(</span>
	<span class="s">"fmt"</span>
	<span class="s">"os"</span>
<span class="p">)</span>

<span class="k">func</span> <span class="n">main</span><span class="p">()</span> <span class="p">{</span>
	<span class="k">var</span> <span class="n">s</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sep</span> <span class="kt">string</span>
	<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">i</span> <span class="o">:=</span> <span class="m">0</span><span class="p">;</span> <span class="n">i</span> <span class="o">&lt;</span> <span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">os</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Args</span><span class="p">);</span> <span class="n">i</span><span class="o">++</span> <span class="p">{</span>
		<span class="n">s</span> <span class="o">+=</span> <span class="n">sep</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">os</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Args</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]</span>
		<span class="n">sep</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s">"</span><span class="se">\n</span><span class="s">"</span>
	<span class="p">}</span>
	<span class="n">fmt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Println</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">s</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="p">}</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>It’s kinda weird we don’t have any parentheses around the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">for</code> loop tho.</p>

<p>Also, using blank identifiers <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">_</code> is best practices.
Like here:</p>
<div class="language-go highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="k">package</span> <span class="n">main</span>

<span class="k">import</span> <span class="p">(</span>
	<span class="s">"fmt"</span>
	<span class="s">"os"</span>
<span class="p">)</span>

<span class="k">func</span> <span class="n">main</span><span class="p">()</span> <span class="p">{</span>
	<span class="n">s</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sep</span> <span class="o">:=</span> <span class="s">""</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s">""</span>
	<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">_</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">arg</span> <span class="o">:=</span> <span class="k">range</span> <span class="n">os</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Args</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="m">0</span><span class="o">:</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="p">{</span>
		<span class="n">s</span> <span class="o">+=</span> <span class="n">sep</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">arg</span>
		<span class="n">sep</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s">" "</span>
	<span class="p">}</span>
	<span class="n">fmt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Println</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">s</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="p">}</span>

</code></pre></div></div>
<p>Every <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">s+=</code> results in a creation of a new string. The garbage collector takes care of the ones no longer necessary.</p>

<p>When dealing with large data, a simpler and more efficient solution would be to use <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">strings.Join</code> from the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">strings</code> package.</p>]]></content><author><name></name></author><category term="learning" /><category term="go" /><summary type="html"><![CDATA[Hello again,]]></summary></entry><entry><title type="html">Learning Go, Day 1</title><link href="http://localhost:4000/learning/go/2024/06/04/learning-go-day1.html" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="Learning Go, Day 1" /><published>2024-06-04T00:00:00-06:00</published><updated>2024-06-04T00:00:00-06:00</updated><id>http://localhost:4000/learning/go/2024/06/04/learning-go-day1</id><content type="html" xml:base="http://localhost:4000/learning/go/2024/06/04/learning-go-day1.html"><![CDATA[<p>Hi There!</p>

<p>Hope you’re doing well.</p>

<p>I am also following the book “The Go Programming Language” by Alan A. A. Donovan &amp; Brian W. Kernighan.
<br />
I will be using this book as a reference to learn Go. If you’re a uni student, you can refer to this book for free from the Oreilly Learning Platform.</p>

<hr />
<p><br />
What I got to know so far:</p>

<p>1) It has garbage collection, a package system, first-class functions, lexical scope, a syscall interface, and immutable strings in text.</p>

<p>2) It has no implicit numerical conversions, no constructors, no destructors either. No operator overloading? No default parameter values? no inheritance? no generics? no exceptions? no macros? no function annotations? no thread-local storage? WTF?! Looks like I got to unlearn a lot of things (🤓☝️)</p>

<p>3) It is backwards compatible, mature and stable.</p>

<p>4) Go is good for concurrent programming, and it has a built-in concurrency model called goroutines.</p>

<hr />
<p><br />
With that, Let’s start with Chapter Numero Uno. :)</p>

<h2 id="11-hello-world">1.1 Hello, World!</h2>

<p>Pretty self explanatory, right? Here’s how you do simple string output in Go:</p>

<div class="language-go highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="k">package</span> <span class="n">main</span>

<span class="k">import</span> <span class="s">"fmt"</span>

<span class="k">func</span> <span class="n">main</span><span class="p">()</span> <span class="p">{</span>
	<span class="n">fmt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Println</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s">"Hello, World!"</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="p">}</span>
</code></pre></div></div>
<hr />
<p><br />
Go is a compiled language. It is Go toolchain’s job to convert a source program and the things it depends on into instructions in the native machine language.
<br />
Another interesting thing is, it natively handles Unicode characters. So, you can use any character from any language in your code.
<br />
Say for instance, you save this code as <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">hello.go</code>, you can run it using:</p>
<div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="nv">$ </span>go build hello.go
<span class="nv">$ </span>./hello
</code></pre></div></div>
<p>or simply:</p>
<div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="nv">$ </span>go run hello.go
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>The book then goes into detail about the program itself. About how Go code is organized into packages, which are similar to libraries or modules in other languages. The <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">main</code> package is special, as it defines a standalone executable program, not a library. Each source file begins with a <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">package</code> declaration, which states which package the file belongs to. The <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">main</code> package is the entry point of the program. Importing a package is done using the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">import</code> keyword. The <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">fmt</code> package is one of the standard library packages that come with Go. It provides functions for formatting text and reading input.</p>

<p>The program will not compile if there are any unused imports or variables. This is to ensure that the code is clean and maintainable.</p>

<p>Go takes formatting seriously. The <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">gofmt</code> tool automatically formats Go code according to a set of rules. This ensures that all Go code looks the same, no matter who wrote it. This is a good thing, as it makes it easier to read and understand code written by others. It is best practice to run <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">gofmt</code> on your code before committing it to version control.</p>

<hr />
<p><br />
That’s it for today. I will be back with more tomorrow.</p>

<p>Cheers,
<br />
Manav</p>]]></content><author><name></name></author><category term="learning" /><category term="go" /><summary type="html"><![CDATA[Hi There!]]></summary></entry><entry><title type="html">Learning Go, Day 0</title><link href="http://localhost:4000/learning/go/2024/06/02/learning-go-day0.html" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="Learning Go, Day 0" /><published>2024-06-02T00:00:00-06:00</published><updated>2024-06-02T00:00:00-06:00</updated><id>http://localhost:4000/learning/go/2024/06/02/learning-go-day0</id><content type="html" xml:base="http://localhost:4000/learning/go/2024/06/02/learning-go-day0.html"><![CDATA[<p>Hi There!</p>

<div class="language-go highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="k">package</span> <span class="n">main</span>
<span class="k">import</span> <span class="s">"fmt"</span>

<span class="k">func</span> <span class="n">main</span><span class="p">()</span> <span class="p">{</span>
    <span class="n">fmt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Println</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s">"Hello, World!"</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="p">}</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>This is how you do simple string output in Go.</p>

<p>I will be following the <a href="https://go.dev/learn/">Official Website</a>, and, down the road, some other online resources I find useful.
<br />
You can use the link above to install everything you need to get started with Go.</p>

<p>I will try my best to document my learning journey here.</p>

<p>Cheers!
<br />
Manav</p>]]></content><author><name></name></author><category term="learning" /><category term="go" /><summary type="html"><![CDATA[Hi There!]]></summary></entry></feed>